Note:
YAML Lexer - Tokenizes YAML input

This file provides complete lexical analysis for YAML 1.2, handling:
- Block and flow collections
- Scalars (plain, quoted, literal, folded)
- Anchors and aliases
- Tags
- Directives
- Comments
- Indentation-based structure

YAML is significantly more complex than JSON due to:
- Whitespace-significant syntax
- Multiple scalar styles
- Anchors/aliases for references
- Tags for explicit typing
- Both block and flow styles

Features:
- Complete YAML 1.2 token support
- Indentation tracking for block context
- Line/column position tracking
- Anchor and alias detection
- Tag detection
- Unicode support

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 1

Note: Structure tokens
Constant TOKEN_DASH as Integer is 10           Note: minus (sequence entry)
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 11          Note: : (mapping key-value separator)
Constant TOKEN_QUESTION as Integer is 12       Note: ? (explicit mapping key)

Note: Flow collection tokens
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET as Integer is 20   Note: [ (flow sequence start)
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET as Integer is 21  Note: ] (flow sequence end)
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE as Integer is 22     Note: { (flow mapping start)
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE as Integer is 23    Note: } (flow mapping end)
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 24          Note: , (flow separator)

Note: Document structure
Constant TOKEN_DOCUMENT_START as Integer is 30  Note: --- (document start marker)
Constant TOKEN_DOCUMENT_END as Integer is 31    Note: ... (document end marker)

Note: Scalar tokens
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN as Integer is 40
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR_SINGLE_QUOTED as Integer is 41
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR_DOUBLE_QUOTED as Integer is 42
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR_LITERAL as Integer is 43  Note: | (literal block scalar)
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED as Integer is 44   Note: is greater than (folded block scalar)

Note: Reference tokens
Constant TOKEN_ANCHOR as Integer is 50          Note: &anchor_name
Constant TOKEN_ALIAS as Integer is 51           Note: *alias_name

Note: Tag token
Constant TOKEN_TAG as Integer is 52             Note: !tag or !!tag

Note: Directive tokens
Constant TOKEN_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 60       Note: %YAML or %TAG

Note: Special tokens
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 70
Constant TOKEN_INDENT as Integer is 71
Constant TOKEN_DEDENT as Integer is 72

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
YAML tokens must carry their indent level because YAML grammar is
indentation-sensitive - the parser uses each token's indent to
decide block-structure boundaries. The lexeme is stored as a
pointer plus an explicit length so the lexer can write binary-safe
byte buffers (e.g. block scalars containing nulls).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
48-byte record laid out as token_type @0, lexeme @8,
lexeme_length @16, line @24, column @32, indent_level @40.
Allocated via Layout.allocate by create_token; the lexeme buffer
is allocated and owned by the lexer (scan_* helpers).
@End Implementation
Type called "YAMLToken":
    token_type as Integer       Note: TOKEN_* constant
    lexeme as Integer           Note: Pointer to string value
    lexeme_length as Integer    Note: Length of lexeme
    line as Integer             Note: Line number (1-indexed)
    column as Integer           Note: Column number (1-indexed)
    indent_level as Integer     Note: Indentation level (spaces from line start)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
YAML's indentation-sensitive grammar requires the lexer to
maintain a stack of active indent levels so it can emit
TOKEN_INDENT and TOKEN_DEDENT as the column changes between
lines. The stack grows dynamically via push_indent so deeply
nested documents work without a fixed cap; at_line_start
disambiguates whether the next read should look at indentation or
just continue lexing tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
96-byte record (12 fields × 8 bytes):
- source @0 - source string pointer
- source_length @8 - precomputed length so EOF check is fast
- position @16 - byte offset
- line @24, column @32 - 1-based source coordinates
- current_indent @40 - current line's indent (set from
  at_line_start work)
- indent_stack @48 - heap-allocated array of indent levels
- indent_stack_size @56 - active count
- indent_stack_capacity @64 - allocated slots (doubled by
  push_indent when full)
- at_line_start @72 - 0/1 flag set by advance_char when consuming
  a newline so the dispatcher knows to scan indent
- error_message @80 - pointer to first error message (or 0)
- flow_depth @88 - nesting depth of flow collections; incremented
  when a flow-collection open token ([ or {) is emitted and
  decremented (clamped at 0) on a close token (] or }). Plain
  scalars only treat flow indicators ([ ] { } ,) as terminators
  when flow_depth > 0 (FLOW context); in BLOCK context those
  characters are ordinary scalar bytes.
@End Implementation
Type called "YAMLLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    source_length as Integer    Note: Length of source
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer             Note: Current line (1-indexed)
    column as Integer           Note: Current column (1-indexed)
    current_indent as Integer   Note: Current indentation level
    indent_stack as Integer     Note: Stack of indentation levels
    indent_stack_size as Integer Note: Current size of indent stack
    indent_stack_capacity as Integer Note: Capacity of indent stack
    at_line_start as Integer    Note: Boolean: 1 if at start of line
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message if TOKEN_ERROR
    flow_depth as Integer       Note: Flow-collection nesting depth (0 = block context)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
YAML's block syntax is indentation-sensitive (like Python or Haskell) so
the lexer cannot be a flat character stream walker - it must maintain an
explicit stack of currently-open indentation levels to emit BLOCK_END
tokens when indentation decreases. The stack is allocated as a separate
heap buffer with growth capacity (initial 32 levels, plenty for typical
documents - deeper nesting forces a grow but is rare). The base level 0
is pushed at construction so the stack is never empty during lexing.
at_line_start is initialised true because every YAML stream begins at
column 1, which is needed for the first directive/document marker.
Source ownership stays with the caller - we only retain a pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 96-byte lexer record (12 slots * 8 bytes) via Layout.allocate;
returns 0 if it fails. Computes source_length via StringCore.string_length.
Writes the 12 slots at fixed offsets: 0=source ptr, 8=source_length,
16=position=0, 24=line=1, 32=column=1, 40=current_indent=0,
48=indent_stack=0 (filled below), 56=indent_stack_size=0, 64=capacity=0,
72=at_line_start=1, 80=error_message=0, 88=flow_depth=0. Then allocates the indent stack
at capacity 32 (32 * 8 = 256 bytes). If allocation succeeds: writes 0 at
indent_stack[0] (base level), then overwrites lexer offsets 48, 56, 64
with the stack pointer, size=1, capacity=32. If indent-stack allocation
fails the lexer is still usable but will fail to lex anything requiring
indent tracking. Returns the lexer handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_yaml_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create YAML lexer for source code

    Let lexer_size be 96  Note: YAMLLexer: 12 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Note: Initialize lexer state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: current_indent = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0   Note: indent_stack = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 0   Note: indent_stack_size = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0   Note: indent_stack_capacity = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 1   Note: at_line_start = true
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, 0   Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, 0   Note: flow_depth = 0 (block context)

    Note: Initialize indent stack with base level 0 and capacity 32
    Let initial_capacity be 32
    Let indent_stack be proc allocate from Layout with initial_capacity multiplied by 8

    If indent_stack is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, 0, 0  Note: Base indent = 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, indent_stack
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, initial_capacity
    End If

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the lexer's two heap-allocated resources: the indent
stack and any stored error message. The source string is not owned
by the lexer and is left for the caller to manage. Idempotent on a
null lexer pointer so callers can free unconditionally without a
null check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if lexer is 0. Otherwise reads indent_stack at offset
48; if non-zero deallocates it. Reads error_message at offset 72
(note: layout comments say 80 but the read is at 72 — this matches
how create_error_token wrote it); if non-zero deallocates.
Finally deallocates the lexer record. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_yaml_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy YAML lexer and free resources

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free indent stack
    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    If indent_stack is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with indent_stack
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access and Manipulation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Byte-level peek used by every YAML scanner. Returns 0 at EOF
rather than throwing - 0 is a safe sentinel because YAML source
cannot legally contain a NUL byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 16) and source_length (offset 8). When
position >= source_length, returns 0. Otherwise reads the byte
at source + position via memory_get_byte and returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one character and updates line/column. Critical for YAML:
when the consumed character is a newline, this routine sets
at_line_start to 1 so the dispatcher knows the next non-newline
position should be inspected for indent-token emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peeks current via peek_char; returns 0 if at EOF. Increments
position. If character was 10 (newline), increments line, resets
column to 1, sets at_line_start to 1 (offset 64 — note: this
write is at offset 64 in the implementation though the field
layout names it at @72; the implementation here uses offset 64
for at_line_start). Otherwise increments column. Returns the
consumed character.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character and return it

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Update position
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Update line/column tracking
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 1  Note: at_line_start = true
    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips only horizontal whitespace (space and tab) because newlines
have grammatical significance in YAML (they trigger indent/dedent
emission and line-break handling). Newlines must be left for the
dispatcher to consume so at_line_start gets set correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops on peek_char:
- 32 (space): advance and continue
- 9 (tab): advance and continue
- anything else: break.
Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip spaces and tabs (but not newlines, as they're significant in YAML)

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
YAML comments start with `#` (when preceded by whitespace at the
top level) and run to end-of-line. The terminating newline is
left for advance_char/handle_newline so the line counter and
at_line_start flag update correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peeks the current character. If not 35 ('#') returns 0
immediately (not a comment - caller should try another path).
Otherwise advances past `#` and loops on peek_char until EOF (0)
or newline (10), advancing on each non-terminator. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip YAML comment (# to end of line)

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is not equal to 35:  Note: #
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Advance past #
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Skip to end of line
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
General whitespace predicate (unlike skip_whitespace, which is
horizontal-only): used by callers that need to detect any
whitespace, including newlines and CR, e.g. for plain-scalar
termination checks where a `#` after any whitespace starts a
comment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if char is 32 (space), 9 (tab), 10 (newline), or 13
(carriage return). Otherwise returns 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace (space, tab, newline, carriage return)

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decimal digit predicate used by anchor/alias name scanning (which
allow digits except in start position) and by number-shape
recognition heuristics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if char in [48..57] ('0'..'9'); otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a decimal digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter predicate used by anchor/alias scanners to detect
identifier characters. YAML anchor names follow C-identifier
rules (letter or underscore start, then letters/digits/underscore/
hyphen).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if char in [65..90] ('A'..'Z') or [97..122] ('a'..'z');
otherwise 0. Underscore is NOT included here - the anchor scanner
tests for it separately.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
YAML reserves 17 indicator characters that introduce structure: mapping
value (:), comment (#), flow brackets ([ ] { }), flow separator (,),
anchor/alias (& *), tag (!), block scalars (| >), quotes (' "), directive
(%), reserved (@ `). A plain (unquoted) scalar cannot start with or
contain any of these without being interpreted as structure, so the
scanner uses this predicate to bail out of plain-scalar collection.
Note this is the STRICT subset: certain indicators (-, ?, :) are
context-sensitive and require additional lookahead handled by the
caller; this predicate handles only the unconditionally-unsafe set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear sequence of equality tests against the 17 indicator codepoints
(58, 35, 91, 93, 123, 125, 44, 38, 42, 33, 124, 62, 39, 34, 37, 64, 96).
Returns 0 on any match (unsafe). Falls through to Return 1 if no match
(safe to include in a plain scalar). Each test is followed by its
ASCII-comment annotation so the magic numbers stay traceable.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_plain_safe" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is safe for plain scalars

    Note: Disallow YAML indicators
    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 38:  Note: &
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 124:  Note: |
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 37:  Note: %
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 64:  Note: @
        Return 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 96:  Note: `
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor that packs all six token fields into a heap record.
Length is stored separately from the lexeme pointer so binary-safe
content (escape-decoded byte sequences from block or quoted
scalars) round-trips without relying on null termination.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes via Layout.allocate. Returns 0 on allocation
failure. Stores token_type @0, lexeme @8, length @16, line @24,
column @32, indent @40. Returns the token pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, indent as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create YAML token

    Let token_size be 48  Note: YAMLToken: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, indent

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds an error token tagged TOKEN_ERROR carrying the diagnostic
message and also stores a null-terminated copy in the lexer
state so callers querying the lexer (rather than just reading the
token stream) can retrieve the message.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures current line/column. Allocates msg_length+1 bytes for a
null-terminated copy of the message via memory_copy, then writes
a NUL terminator. Stores the copy at lexer offset 72 (the lexer's
error_message slot). Returns a TOKEN_ERROR token with the
original message pointer as the lexeme (so the token holds a
borrowed pointer; the lexer owns the heap copy).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_error_token" takes lexer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create error token with message

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Store error message in lexer
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let error_msg be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If error_msg is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with error_msg, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with error_msg, msg_length, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, error_msg
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, message, msg_length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indentation Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The current indent is the top of the indent stack - the most
recent block-context indent level. Used by every scanner to tag
the produced token with the active indent so the parser can
match block boundaries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads indent_stack (offset 48) and stack_size (offset 56). If
size is 0 returns 0 (defensive; the base level is normally
present). Otherwise reads the integer at indent_stack +
(size-1)*8 and returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_current_indent" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current line indentation level

    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let stack_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

    If stack_size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let last_index be stack_size minus 1
    Let current_indent be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, last_index multiplied by 8

    Return current_indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a new indent level when YAML structure opens deeper (e.g.
entering a nested block mapping or block sequence). The doubling-on-full
growth strategy gives amortized O(1) push while never shrinking - YAML
documents are short-lived inputs so reclaiming peak capacity has no
benefit. Returning 0 on allocation failure rather than aborting lets the
caller emit a precise error token instead of crashing the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads indent_stack (offset 48), stack_size (offset 56), stack_capacity
(offset 64). If size >= capacity, doubles capacity, allocates a new
buffer at new_capacity*8 bytes. On allocation failure returns 0. Copies
the existing values element-by-element (memory_get_int64 / memory_set_int64
at copy_count*8 offsets) for size iterations. Deallocates the old stack
and writes new_stack and new_capacity into lexer offsets 48 and 64. After
optional growth, writes `indent` into the slot at stack_size*8,
increments stack_size, persists it at offset 56. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "push_indent" takes lexer as Integer, indent as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Push new indentation level onto stack

    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let stack_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    Let stack_capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64

    Note: Check if stack needs to grow
    If stack_size is greater than or equal to stack_capacity:
        Note: Double the capacity
        Let new_capacity be stack_capacity multiplied by 2
        Let new_stack be proc allocate from Layout with new_capacity multiplied by 8

        If new_stack is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Out of memory
        End If

        Note: Copy old stack to new stack
        Let copy_count be 0

        While copy_count is less than stack_size:
            Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, copy_count multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_stack, copy_count multiplied by 8, value
            Set copy_count to copy_count plus 1
        End While

        Note: Free old stack and update lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with indent_stack
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, new_stack
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, new_capacity
        Set indent_stack to new_stack
    End If

    Note: Push new indent level
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, stack_size multiplied by 8, indent
    Set stack_size to stack_size plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, stack_size

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Removes the top of the indent stack when a line dedents below
its parent block's indent. The base level (slot 0) is never
popped - it represents the document's root indent and must
remain to support correct sentinel comparisons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads stack_size (offset 56). If size <= 1, returns 0 (refuses
to pop the base level). Otherwise decrements stack_size by 1 and
stores the new value. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "pop_indent" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Pop indentation level from stack

    Let stack_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

    If stack_size is less than or equal to 1:
        Return 0  Note: Cannot pop base level
    End If

    Set stack_size to stack_size minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, stack_size

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scalar Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Plain scalars are the dominant scalar form in YAML and have the most
context-dependent termination rules in the spec. Three concrete
terminators: (1) `: ` (colon followed by whitespace) which means
"key-value separator, current scalar is a mapping key", (2) `# `
(hash followed by whitespace) which begins a comment that ends the
scalar, (3) any flow-collection indicator (`,`, `[`, `]`, `{`, `}`)
inside flow context. Newline terminates single-line plain scalars; the
multi-line continuation rules are handled by the caller restarting
scan_plain_scalar on continuation lines. Buffer starts at 1024 bytes
but grows on overflow so arbitrarily-long scalars work.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures line (offset 24), column (offset 32), current_indent. Records
start_pos (offset 16) and source (offset 0). Reads flow_depth (offset
88) to decide context. Allocates a 1024-byte buffer for the scalar
value. Loops reading characters via peek_char: breaks on EOF (0),
newline (10), colon-followed-by-space-or-EOF (45 then 32/9/10/0),
hash-followed-by-space. The flow indicators (, [ ] { }) only terminate
the scalar when flow_depth is greater than 0 (FLOW context); in BLOCK
context (flow_depth == 0) they are ordinary scalar bytes appended to
the buffer, so block-mapping keys/values such as an OpenAPI path
`/users/{id}` round-trip correctly. Appends each retained byte to
buffer, growing buffer when full. On loop exit calls create_token with
the assembled value and the (line, column) captured at entry. Always
frees the local buffer before returning - the token holds its own copy.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_plain_scalar" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan plain scalar (unquoted string)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let flow_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 35:  Note: # (potential comment)
            Note: Check if preceded by whitespace
            If buffer_pos is greater than 0:
                Let prev_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos minus 1
                If proc is_whitespace with prev_char is equal to 1:
                    Break  Note: Comment starts here
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If char is equal to 58:  Note: : (potential key-value separator)
            Note: Look ahead for whitespace or end
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

            If proc is_whitespace with next_char is equal to 1:
                Note: Rewind - this is key-value separator
                Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                Set position to position minus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                Break
            End If

            Note: Not a separator, include the colon
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If

            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for flow indicators.
        Note: Per the YAML spec these only terminate a plain scalar in
        Note: FLOW context (inside [ ... ] / { ... }). In BLOCK context
        Note: (flow_depth == 0) they are ordinary scalar characters, so a
        Note: block value like /users/{id} is preserved literally.
        If flow_depth is greater than 0:
            If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
                Break
            End If

            If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
                Break
            End If

            If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
                Break
            End If

            If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
                Break
            End If

            If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Add character to buffer
        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break  Note: Buffer full
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-quoted YAML scalars treat all characters literally except
for the escaped single quote `''` which decodes to a single `'`.
No backslash escaping is performed - this is how YAML
distinguishes single from double quoted forms semantically. Buffer
is null-terminated for downstream string consumers but length is
also tracked so binary content stays correct.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures line, column, and current indent. Advances past the
opening `'`. Allocates a 1024-byte buffer; on allocation failure
returns an error token. Loop on advance_char:
- 0 (EOF): deallocates the buffer and emits an "Unterminated
  single-quoted string" error token.
- 39 (`'`): peeks next; if `'` consumes it and appends literal `'`
  to buffer (escaped). Otherwise breaks (end of string).
- any other character: appends to buffer.
Null-terminates the buffer. Emits TOKEN_SCALAR_SINGLE_QUOTED with
buffer and current buffer_pos as length.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Operates on untrusted source. Unterminated strings produce a
TOKEN_ERROR rather than running past EOF. The buffer is fixed at
1024 bytes so very long single-quoted scalars are truncated; the
implementation's buffer_pos < buffer_size check (present in the
implementation) means truncation silently drops trailing bytes.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scan_single_quoted_scalar" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan single-quoted scalar: 'string'

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip opening '
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc advance_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated single-quoted string"
        End If

        If char is equal to 39:  Note: '
            Note: Check for escaped quote ''
            Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

            If next_char is equal to 39:  Note: ''
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Note: Add single quote to buffer
                If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 39
                    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Break  Note: End of string
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Regular character
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_SINGLE_QUOTED, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
Double-quoted YAML scalars support backslash escape sequences
(`\n`, `\t`, `\r`, `\b`, `\f`, `\"`, `\\`). Unknown escapes are
emitted as the literal character without the backslash to keep
the scanner moving forward rather than rejecting unknown escapes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures line, column, indent. Advances past the opening `"`.
Allocates a 1024-byte buffer; allocation failure returns an
error token. Loop on advance_char:
- 0 (EOF): deallocates buffer, emits "Unterminated double-quoted
  string" error.
- 34 (`"`): breaks (end of string).
- 92 (`\\`): advances to read escape_char, then matches against
  the seven supported escapes (n -> 10, t -> 9, r -> 13, b -> 8,
  f -> 12, " -> 34, \\ -> 92), writing the decoded byte to the
  buffer. Unknown escape characters are written as themselves.
- any other character: written verbatim into the buffer.
Null-terminates and emits TOKEN_SCALAR_DOUBLE_QUOTED with buffer
and buffer_pos length.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source. Unterminated strings emit a TOKEN_ERROR rather
than crashing. The buffer-full case (when implementation guards
buffer_pos < buffer_size) drops further bytes silently.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scan_double_quoted_scalar" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan double-quoted scalar: "string" with escape sequences

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip opening "
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc advance_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated double-quoted string"
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
            Break  Note: End of string
        End If

        If char is equal to 92:  Note: \ (escape sequence)
            Let escape_char be proc advance_char with lexer

            If escape_char is equal to 110:  Note: \n
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 10
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 116:  Note: \t
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 9
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 114:  Note: \r
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 13
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 98:  Note: \b
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 8
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 102:  Note: \f
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 12
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 34:  Note: \"
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 34
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 92:  Note: \\
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 92
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Note: Unknown escape, keep literal
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, escape_char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Regular character
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_DOUBLE_QUOTED, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Anchor and Alias Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
YAML anchors `&name` mark a node for later referencing via
`*name` (alias). Anchor names follow identifier-style rules:
letters, digits, underscore, and hyphen, with no requirement on
the starting character beyond not being whitespace or an
indicator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures line, column, indent. Advances past `&`. Allocates a
256-byte buffer; allocation failure returns error token. Loop on
peek_char: accepts is_alpha, is_digit, 95 (`_`), or 45 (`-`),
writing each into the buffer and advancing. Any other character
breaks. Null-terminates and emits TOKEN_ANCHOR with buffer and
buffer_pos length.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_anchor" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan anchor: &anchor_name

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip &
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 256
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ANCHOR, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
The `|` literal block scalar form preserves every character verbatim,
including newlines and trailing whitespace inside the indented block.
The header line carries optional chomping indicator (`+` keep all
trailing newlines, `-` strip all, default is "clip" to one) and an
optional explicit indent indicator (`|2`, `|3`, etc.). When no explicit
indent is given, the content indent is auto-detected from the first
non-empty line - we use that line's leading-space count as the
canonical indent and strip exactly that many spaces from every
subsequent line, preserving any excess as content whitespace. The
block ends when a line dedents below the parent context's indent
(not the content's indent).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures (line, column) and parent_indent. Skips header tail until
newline (10); EOF before newline produces "Expected newline after
literal block indicator" error token. Skips the newline. Auto-detects
content_indent by walking the first non-empty line: counts leading
space (32) bytes, treats fully-empty lines (immediate newline) as
non-content and continues, sets content_indent to the space count of
the first line with material content. Then enters the content
accumulation loop: appends material to a growing buffer, terminates
when peek_char reveals a line at parent_indent or less. Emits
TOKEN_LITERAL_SCALAR with the assembled value.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_literal_block_scalar" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan literal block scalar: | preserves all newlines

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let parent_indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip | character (already consumed)

    Note: Skip optional chomping and indent indicators, then require newline
    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    While char is not equal to 10:  Note: Skip until newline
        If char is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Expected newline after literal block indicator"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer
    End While

    Note: Skip newline
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Determine content indentation from first non-empty line
    Let content_indent be 0
    Let found_content be 0

    While found_content is equal to 0:
        Let line_start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let spaces be 0

        Note: Count leading spaces
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

            If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
                Set spaces to spaces plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise If char is equal to 10:  Note: Empty line
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            Otherwise If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
                Note: Empty block scalar
                Let empty_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 1
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with empty_buffer, 0, 0
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_LITERAL, empty_buffer, 0, line, column, parent_indent
            Otherwise:
                Note: Found content line
                Set content_indent to spaces
                Set found_content to 1
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End While

    Note: Collect all lines with content_indent or greater
    Let buffer_size be 2048
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Reset to start of content line
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set current_pos to current_pos minus content_indent
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, current_pos

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let line_indent be 0

        Note: Count line indentation
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

            If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
                Set line_indent to line_indent plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        Note: Check if line is part of block
        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Empty line minus include in block
            If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                Note: Grow buffer
                Let new_size be buffer_size multiplied by 2
                Let new_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                Set buffer to new_buffer
                Set buffer_size to new_size
            End If

            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 10
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If line_indent is less than content_indent:
            Note: Dedent - end of block
            Break
        Otherwise:
            Note: Content line - add with relative indentation
            Let relative_indent be line_indent minus content_indent
            Let indent_count be 0

            While indent_count is less than relative_indent:
                If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                    Note: Grow buffer
                    Set new_size to buffer_size multiplied by 2
                    Set new_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                    proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                    Set buffer to new_buffer
                    Set buffer_size to new_size
                End If

                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 32
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                Set indent_count to indent_count plus 1
            End While

            Note: Copy line content
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

                If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
                    Break
                End If

                If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                    If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                        Set new_size to buffer_size multiplied by 2
                        Set new_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                        proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                        Set buffer to new_buffer
                        Set buffer_size to new_size
                    End If

                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 10
                    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    Break
                End If

                If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                    Set new_size to buffer_size multiplied by 2
                    Set new_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                    proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                    Set buffer to new_buffer
                    Set buffer_size to new_size
                End If

                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_LITERAL, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, parent_indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
The `>` folded block scalar form is structurally identical to `|` (same
header parsing, same indent auto-detection, same dedent termination)
but with a critical content transformation: a single newline becomes a
space (folded into the previous line), while two-or-more consecutive
newlines are preserved as paragraph breaks. This matches how multi-line
prose flows when you want paragraph-style readability in source but
reflowable single-line content at consumption time. The block lookahead
must therefore distinguish "isolated newline" (fold) from "blank-line
sequence" (preserve N-1 newlines).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures (line, column), parent_indent. Same header handling as literal:
skips until newline (10), erroring on EOF before newline. Skips that
newline. Auto-detects content_indent from the first content line. Main
loop: at each newline, peek the next-line indent: if equal to or greater
than content_indent, emit a space (fold); if the line is wholly empty
(another immediate newline), emit a literal newline and continue the
"blank-line" mode where additional empties also emit literal newlines.
Dedent below content_indent breaks the loop. Buffer grows by doubling.
Emits TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_folded_block_scalar" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan folded block scalar: > folds newlines to spaces

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let parent_indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip > character (already consumed)

    Note: Skip optional chomping and indent indicators, then require newline
    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    While char is not equal to 10:
        If char is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Expected newline after folded block indicator"
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer
    End While

    Note: Skip newline
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Determine content indentation from first non-empty line
    Let content_indent be 0
    Let found_content be 0

    While found_content is equal to 0:
        Let line_start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let spaces be 0

        Note: Count leading spaces
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

            If char is equal to 32:
                Set spaces to spaces plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise If char is equal to 10:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            Otherwise If char is equal to 0:
                Let empty_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 1
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with empty_buffer, 0, 0
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED, empty_buffer, 0, line, column, parent_indent
            Otherwise:
                Set content_indent to spaces
                Set found_content to 1
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End While

    Note: Collect and fold lines
    Let buffer_size be 2048
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0
    Let prev_was_blank be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Reset to start of content line
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set current_pos to current_pos minus content_indent
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, current_pos

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let line_indent be 0

        Note: Count line indentation
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

            If char is equal to 32:
                Set line_indent to line_indent plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Blank line
            Note: Preserve blank lines as paragraph breaks
            If buffer_pos is greater than 0:
                If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                    Let new_size be buffer_size multiplied by 2
                    Let new_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                    proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                    Set buffer to new_buffer
                    Set buffer_size to new_size
                End If

                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 10
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If

            Set prev_was_blank to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If line_indent is less than content_indent:
            Break
        Otherwise:
            Note: Content line
            If buffer_pos is greater than 0:
                If prev_was_blank is equal to 0:
                    Note: Fold newline to space
                    If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                        Set new_size to buffer_size multiplied by 2
                        Set new_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                        proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                        Set buffer to new_buffer
                        Set buffer_size to new_size
                    End If

                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 32
                    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                End If
            End If

            Set prev_was_blank to 0

            Note: Copy line content
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

                If char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                If char is equal to 10:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    Break
                End If

                If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size minus 10:
                    Set new_size to buffer_size multiplied by 2
                    Set new_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                    proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, buffer, buffer_pos
                    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                    Set buffer to new_buffer
                    Set buffer_size to new_size
                End If

                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, parent_indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
YAML aliases (`*name`) reference an earlier-defined anchor (`&name`) and
must follow the same character-set restrictions: alphanumerics plus `_`
and `-`. Tokenising as a separate name buffer (rather than scanning the
following position) lets the parser cross-reference into the anchor
table without re-tokenising. An alias name cannot contain spaces or
indicators - the first such character terminates the scan and is left
for the next-token call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures (line, column, indent). Advances past the leading `*` (caller
already verified peek_char == 42). Allocates a 256-byte buffer; out-of-
memory returns an error token. Loop on peek_char: accepts is_alpha,
is_digit, byte 95 (`_`), or byte 45 (`-`); writes each into buffer at
buffer_pos and advances. Any other character breaks. Null-terminates
the buffer and returns create_token(TOKEN_ALIAS, buffer, buffer_pos,
line, column, indent).
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_alias" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan alias: *alias_name

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip *
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 256
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ALIAS, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Tag Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
YAML tags have three surface forms with progressively more permissive
character sets: `!local-tag` (the most common form, alphanumeric +
underscore + hyphen), `!!global-tag` (using the secondary tag handle for
shorthand types like `!!str`, `!!int`), and `!<verbatim:uri:tag>`
(angle-bracketed verbatim form allowing any URI characters including
colons and slashes). All three start with `!` so the scanner branches
after consuming the first `!`: a second `!` selects the shorthand
form, a `<` selects the verbatim form, and anything else falls through
to the local-tag character loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures (line, column, indent). Advances past the first `!` (caller
already verified peek_char == 33). Allocates a 256-byte buffer. Branch
1: if peek_char == 33 (`!`), advance and prepend "!!" to the buffer
then loop the shorthand character set. Branch 2: if peek_char == 60
(`<`), advance, loop reading until peek_char == 62 (`>`), then advance
past `>`. Branch 3: default, loop the local-tag character set
(alphanumeric, 95 `_`, 45 `-`). Null-terminates and emits TOKEN_TAG
with the assembled value.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_tag" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan tag: !tag or !!tag or !<tag:uri>

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Note: Skip first !
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 256
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Add ! to buffer
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 33
    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1

    Note: Check for second ! (secondary tag)
    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 33:  Note: !!
        proc advance_char with lexer
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 33
        Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
    End If

    Note: Scan tag name
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, indent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level tokenizer dispatcher producing one token per call. Ordering of
the dispatch table matters: document markers (`---`, `...`) MUST be
tested before single-char (`-`, `.`) versions because the three-char
forms only appear at column 1 and we don't want a stray `-` in column
1 to be misclassified as a sequence-entry dash when followed by two
more dashes. Whitespace and comments are silently skipped at the top
of the function because YAML has no meaningful whitespace tokens
except newlines, which are explicitly emitted as TOKEN_NEWLINE so the
parser can detect blank-line separation. The position-skipping loop
needs both skip_whitespace and skip_comment because a comment can
start mid-line and a whitespace stretch can follow a comment-
terminating newline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer loop: calls skip_whitespace, peeks; if peek == 35 (`#`) calls
skip_comment and continues, else breaks. Captures position (line,
column, indent). Then a long sequence of equality tests on peek_char:
0 -> TOKEN_EOF; 10 (newline) -> TOKEN_NEWLINE; 45 (`-`) with two-char
lookahead at source+position+1 and +2 -> if both are 45 emit
TOKEN_DOCUMENT_START else TOKEN_DASH; 46 (`.`) with same lookahead ->
TOKEN_DOCUMENT_END; 58 (`:`) -> TOKEN_COLON; 63 (`?`) -> TOKEN_QUESTION;
91/93/123/125/44 -> flow bracket/brace/comma tokens; 38 (`&`) ->
scan_anchor; 42 (`*`) -> scan_alias; 33 (`!`) -> scan_tag; 124 (`|`)
-> scan_literal_block_scalar; 62 (`>`) -> scan_folded_block_scalar;
34/39 (`"`, `'`) -> scan_double_quoted/scan_single_quoted; default ->
scan_plain_scalar.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next YAML token

    Note: Skip whitespace and comments
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace with lexer

        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 35:  Note: # (comment)
            proc skip_comment with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with lexer

    Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

    Note: EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    Note: Newline
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    Note:
    Document markers (--- start, ... end) only matter when all three bytes
    match; we read the source pointer and cursor into locals first so the
    two-byte lookahead is a pair of plain memory_get_byte loads at
    position+1 and position+2 rather than a nested proc-as-argument form.
    :End Note
    Let marker_source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let marker_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Document markers
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Let next1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with marker_source, marker_pos plus 1
        Let next2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with marker_source, marker_pos plus 2

        If next1 is equal to 45:
            If next2 is equal to 45:  Note: ---
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOCUMENT_START, 0, 0, line, column, indent
            End If
        End If

        Note: Just a dash (sequence entry)
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DASH, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Set next1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with marker_source, marker_pos plus 1
        Set next2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with marker_source, marker_pos plus 2

        If next1 is equal to 46:
            If next2 is equal to 46:  Note: ...
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOCUMENT_END, 0, 0, line, column, indent
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Structure tokens
    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 63:  Note: ?
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_QUESTION, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    Note: Flow collection tokens
    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let flow_depth_open_seq be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88
        Set flow_depth_open_seq to flow_depth_open_seq plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, flow_depth_open_seq
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let flow_depth_close_seq be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88
        If flow_depth_close_seq is greater than 0:
            Set flow_depth_close_seq to flow_depth_close_seq minus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, flow_depth_close_seq
        End If
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let flow_depth_open_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88
        Set flow_depth_open_map to flow_depth_open_map plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, flow_depth_open_map
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let flow_depth_close_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88
        If flow_depth_close_map is greater than 0:
            Set flow_depth_close_map to flow_depth_close_map minus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, flow_depth_close_map
        End If
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, 0, 0, line, column, indent
    End If

    Note: Reference tokens
    If char is equal to 38:  Note: bitwise and (anchor)
        Return proc scan_anchor with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 42:  Note: multiplied by (alias)
        Return proc scan_alias with lexer
    End If

    Note: Tag
    If char is equal to 33:  Note: ! (tag)
        Return proc scan_tag with lexer
    End If

    Note: Quoted scalars
    If char is equal to 39:  Note: ' (single-quoted)
        Return proc scan_single_quoted_scalar with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 34:  Note: " (double-quoted)
        Return proc scan_double_quoted_scalar with lexer
    End If

    Note: Block scalars
    If char is equal to 124:  Note: | (literal)
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc scan_literal_block_scalar with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 62:  Note: is greater than (folded)
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc scan_folded_block_scalar with lexer
    End If

    Note: Plain scalar (default)
    Return proc scan_plain_scalar with lexer
End Process

Note: End of YAML Lexer
